context: All the major British cities had flourishing department stores by the mid-or late nineteenth century. Increasingly, <a0_0><b5_0>women<b5_0/><a0_0/> became the major shoppers and middle-class households. <a1_0><b6_0>Kendals (formerly Kendal Milne & Faulkner)<b6_0/><a1_0/> in Manchester lays claim to being one of the first department stores and is still known to many of its customers as Kendal's, despite its 2005 name change to <a2_0><b7_0>House of Fraser<b7_0/><a2_0/>. The Manchester institution dates back to <a3_0><b8_0>1836<b8_0/><a3_0/> but had been trading as Watts Bazaar since 1796. At its zenith the store had buildings on both sides of Deansgate linked by a subterranean passage "Kendals Arcade" and an art nouveau tiled food hall. The store was especially known for its emphasis on quality and style over low prices giving it the nickname "the Harrods of the North", although this was due in part to <a4_0><b9_0>Harrods<b9_0/><a4_0/> acquiring the store in 1919. Other large Manchester stores included Paulden's (currently Debenhams) and Lewis's (now a Primark).
